<article>
    <h1>NO-FRILLS DIM SUM</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200724/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-24"><time>2020-07-24</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | HAPPENINGS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>For dim sum that of­fers plenty of value, head to Yeap Seng Hand­made Pau Tim at Bis­han North Shop­ping Mall. Only take­away is avail­able.</p>
    <p>The real win­ner here is the yam ball or wu kok ($0.90). This item alone is worth bust­ing your calo­rie count. But try the other fried snacks be­fore you eat the yam ball or you may not en­joy them as much.</p>
    <p>Sec­ond-gen­er­a­tion owner</p>
    <p>Al­lan Oh, 39, says Thai yam is used. Tem­per­a­ture con­trol of the oil for deep-fry­ing is crit­i­cal in achiev­ing the crispy net-like crust which is pure yam. No flour or bat­ter is used to coat the yam ball.</p>
    <p>Yeap Seng also uses chilled In­done­sian pork, which costs more than frozen pork. The dif­fer­ence in qual­ity is ob­vi­ous, es­pe­cially in items such as siew mai ($0.80).</p>
    <p>The steamed pork dumplings are fat, dumpy and look quite dull. But the pork fill­ing, which is merely mar­i­nated in light soya sauce, white pep­per, salt and su­gar, tastes de­light­fully fresh and has no trace of that meaty odour you find in poor-qual­ity siew mai.</p>
    <p>Other snack-wor­thy items are the chive and pork dumpling ($0.90) and prawn frit­ter ($0.90).</p>
    <p>The prawn frit­ter does not ac­tu­ally con­tain prawn but mar­i­nated squid paste with diced car­rot. Its crispy skin holds up fairly well even for take­away.</p>
    <p>WHERE: Yeap Seng Hand­made Pau Tim, 01-117 Bis­han North Shop­ping Mall, Block 282 Bis­han Street 22 MRT: Bis­han</p>
    <p>OPEN: 6.30am to 12.30pm.</p>
    <p>Closed on Mon­days</p>

